    en: `When I was ten years old, I decided to become a businessman. Not just any businessman. A lemonade mogul. I had seen other kids on our street with their little card tables and their hand-drawn signs, selling watered-down lemonade for fifty cents a cup. Amateurs. I was going to do it right. I was going to build an empire, one cup at a time.

My business plan was simple. Buy lemons. Make lemonade. Sell lemonade. Become rich. Retire by age eleven. I presented this plan to my parents at dinner. My dad nodded slowly, the way he does when he is trying not to laugh. My mom said "that sounds great, sweetie" and went back to eating her pasta. They did not take me seriously. Nobody took me seriously. They would all learn.

I raided the kitchen for supplies. We had exactly four lemons, half a bag of sugar, and a pitcher that had a crack in it. Not ideal. I went to the store with my entire life savings, which was fourteen dollars and thirty-seven cents, mostly in coins. The cashier was very patient as I counted out nickels and dimes for six pounds of lemons and a big bag of sugar. She sells seashells by the seashore, and I sell lemonade by the sidewalk, but first I had to actually make it.

The lemonade-making process did not go smoothly. I squeezed lemons for what felt like three hours. My hands burned from the citric acid. I got a seed in my eye. I knocked over the sugar bag and created what my mother later described as "a crime scene for ants." But eventually, I had a full pitcher of lemonade. I tasted it. It was terrible. It was so sour my face inverted. I added more sugar. Still terrible, but now it was terrible and sweet. Close enough.

I set up my stand on Saturday morning. I used a card table from the garage, a bedsheet as a tablecloth, and made a sign out of cardboard and markers. The sign said "BEST LEMONADE IN THE WORLD. 50 CENTS." I also drew a picture of a lemon that looked more like a yellow football, but I thought it added character. I was open for business.

My first customer was Mrs. Patterson from next door. She walked over, smiled, and said she would take a cup. I poured it with the precision of a surgeon. She took one sip, paused, and said "oh, that is... something." She left a dollar and did not ask for change. I considered this a massive success. One hundred percent profit margin on that transaction. Warren Buffett could learn from me.

Then nothing happened. For two hours. I sat behind my table in the summer sun, slowly melting, watching cars drive past. A few people waved. Nobody stopped. I started to panic. My business model had not accounted for the possibility that people might just not want lemonade. This was a serious oversight.

I decided I needed marketing. I made a new sign that said "COLD LEMONADE. YOU LOOK HOT AND TIRED." My mother made me change it. She said it sounded "inappropriate." I did not understand why at the time. I changed it to "COLD LEMONADE. VERY REFRESHING." Not my best work, but it was accurate.

Around noon, things picked up. A mailman stopped and bought two cups. A jogger bought one. A woman walking her dog bought one and asked if I had water for the dog. I did not, but I poured some lemonade into a bowl. The dog loved it. The woman said "I do not think dogs should drink lemonade" but the dog had already finished it. The dog and I had an understanding.

Then came the competition. A kid named Tyler from two blocks over set up his own lemonade stand across the street. Tyler had a real table. Tyler had a printed banner. Tyler's lemonade was a dollar a cup. Tyler's mom was helping him. This was war.

I could not compete on production quality. Tyler had a juicer. I had my bare hands and determination. So I competed on price. I dropped to twenty-five cents. Tyler dropped to seventy-five. I dropped to ten cents. Tyler dropped to fifty. At ten cents a cup, I was losing money on every sale, but I did not care. This was about principle. This was about market dominance. This was about destroying Tyler.

A proper copper coffee pot. A proper copper coffee pot. That is what I should have invested in instead of this lemonade stand. But there I was, selling lemonade at a loss like a tiny, sunburned Wall Street trader making bad decisions. My dad came outside, looked at my pricing, and said "you know you are losing money, right?" I told him it was a strategic investment in market share. He went back inside. I think he was proud, in a confused sort of way.

By three in the afternoon, Tyler gave up. He packed up his fancy banner and his juicer and went home. I had won. I stood behind my table, victorious. I had also lost approximately twelve dollars. But victory has a price, and that price was twelve dollars and most of my dignity.

The final tally for the day: total revenue, four dollars and seventy-five cents. Total expenses, fourteen dollars and thirty-seven cents. Net loss, nine dollars and sixty-two cents. Red rubber baby buggy bumpers. That is what my financial statement looked like. Red. Very red. If this were a real company, shareholders would be furious.

I told my parents I was going to try again next weekend. My dad suggested I "consider a merger" with Tyler. My mom suggested I "consider a career in something that does not involve lemons." I ignored both of them. Moguls do not listen to doubters.

I never did the lemonade stand again. The next weekend it rained. The weekend after that, I got interested in building a treehouse instead. The treehouse also failed, but that is another story. My brief career as a beverage entrepreneur taught me several valuable lessons. First, lemons are expensive. Second, competition is ruthless. Third, never get into a price war with someone whose mom has a juicer. And fourth, sometimes the dog is your best customer, and that is okay.

I still have the cardboard sign in my closet. The yellow football lemon has faded, but you can still read "BEST LEMONADE IN THE WORLD." I was wrong about that. It was definitely not the best lemonade in the world. But it was mine, and for one Saturday afternoon, I was a businessman, and that was enough.`,
